# Camera and seated-reader test plan

This protocol measures risk reduction. It cannot establish universal camera resistance.

## Fixed setup record

Record these before testing:

- monitor make/model, physical size, resolution, refresh rate, scaling, brightness, HDR setting;
- room illumination and major reflections;
- PDF zoom and font size;
- phone make/model, OS, camera app, lens, photo/video mode, resolution, HDR/night/AI settings;
- exact screen-to-eye and screen-to-camera distances;
- DeskShield method and all control values.

Use the included synthetic PDF so no confidential data enters test evidence.

## Test distances

- **0.3 m:** seated-reader baseline
- **1 m:** nearby observer/phone
- **2 m:** across a small room
- **3 m:** long office line of sight

Mark the camera angle and distance so every method is compared from the same position.

## Matrix

For every distance, capture:

1. Unprotected still photo.
2. Seated-user clarity at 100, 75, 50, and lowest comfortable value.
3. Mouse-over oval and full-row windows at chosen size.
4. Rolling bands at 100% strength and 60, 30, and 20 fps.
5. Rolling bands at the best rate with 1× and available optical/telephoto zoom.
6. At least a five-second video for Unprotected and best Rolling bands.
7. If available, repeat with HDR/night/scene optimization off and on.

Repeat the best-looking protected result three times. Camera pipelines can choose different exposure timing between captures.

## Measurements

### Human seated readability

Give the seated reader ten randomly selected words and five numbers from the page. Record:

- correct words/numbers;
- time to read;
- comfort score from 1 (unusable) to 5 (comfortable).

Target for a usable setting: at least 95% correct and comfort 4 or higher.

### Distant human readability

From 1, 2, and 3 m, record the same measures without zoom aids. Use a different word/number set at each distance.

### Captured-image readability

For each saved capture:

- inspect at normal size and allowed digital zoom;
- manually transcribe the same test strings;
- run one named OCR engine if available;
- record character accuracy, not merely “readable/unreadable.”

A useful result is a large, repeatable reduction versus Unprotected while seated readability stays above target. Decide the competition claim only after reviewing all repetitions.

## Failure cases to seek

Actively test:

- phone very close to the monitor;
- optical/telephoto zoom;
- burst mode or repeated stills;
- HDR/night/long-exposure processing;
- video frame stepping;
- alternate camera angle;
- higher PDF zoom;
- different monitor brightness;
- screenshot or screen-sharing capture.

Document failures in the demo. They make the product boundary credible and identify the next engineering work.

